{#- VARIANT DETAIL (definition) — plain-terms prose body -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="qbo-feat-payroll-definition" style="padding-top:24px;">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom:8px;">In plain terms</div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:18px;">What QuickBooks Online Payroll is, plainly.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>QuickBooks Online Payroll is an Intuit add-on subscription that runs payroll inside QuickBooks Online. It isn&rsquo;t part of a plain QuickBooks subscription &mdash; you add it on, choosing a tier (Core, Premium, or Elite) for the level of service you need. Once it&rsquo;s set up with your employees and tax details, Intuit&rsquo;s service calculates each run: gross pay, withholdings, employer taxes, and net pay.</p>
      <p>For subscribers, that service does more than calculate. It <em>files and pays</em> federal and state payroll taxes on the schedule those agencies require, sends employee pay by <em>direct deposit</em>, and posts each payroll run to your chart of accounts &mdash; so wages, employer taxes, and the matching payroll liabilities land in the books automatically rather than being keyed in by hand. The processing, the tax filing, and the direct deposit are <em>Intuit&rsquo;s</em> service performing as the subscription provides.</p>
      <p>It&rsquo;s worth being precise about the split, because it&rsquo;s where confusion lives. Intuit&rsquo;s payroll service processes payroll and files payroll taxes for subscribers; an independent ProAdvisor firm like ours does not. What we do is set payroll up correctly, keep the books and <a href="/glossary/payroll-liabilities/">payroll liabilities</a> reconciled, and coordinate &mdash; we don&rsquo;t process or file your payroll taxes, and genuinely complex multi-state situations may need a CPA or payroll specialist. We describe QuickBooks Online Payroll as it actually works &mdash; we don&rsquo;t claim to run a service that is Intuit&rsquo;s.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

